[1]
Date: 25 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hong Kong Department of Health 25 Mar 2003
<http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/new/index.htm>

Health Surveillance for airline passengers
-------------------
A spokesman for the Department of Health (DH) 25 Mar 2003 called on members
of the public who had travelled from Hong Kong to Beijing in flight CA 112
on 15 Mar 2003 or from Beijing to Hong Kong in flight CA 115 on 19 Mar 2003
to call DH's hotline 2961 8968 for health advice.
The plea follows the detection of 9 atypical pneumonia cases among members
of a Beijing tour organized by a Hong Kong travel agent.
The tour comprised 35 tour members and a staff member of the travel agent.
They left for Beijing in flight CA 112 on 15 Mar 2003 and returned to Hong
Kong in flight CA 115 on 19 Mar 2003.
Investigation revealed that a couple who joined the tour, both aged 44, had
developed symptoms during their stay in Beijing on 18 Mar 2003. They were
admitted to Tuen Mun Hospital on the evening of 22 Mar 2003 and are now in
stable condition.
On receiving the notification on 23 Mar 2003, DH immediately contacted
other members of the tour. Among them 3, one man and 2 women aged between
27 and 50, were also confirmed to have developed atypical pneumonia
symptoms. They were admitted to Tuen Mun Hospital and Pamela Youde
Nethersole Eastern Hospital for treatment. They are in stable condition.
6 other members of the tour who had been reported to have coughs, 3 men and
3 women aged between 32 and 61, were admitted to hospitals for close
surveillance earlier. Four of them, comprising 2 men and 2 women aged
between 32 and 51, were confirmed today to have infected with atypical
pneumonia. They are receiving treatment in Queen Elizabeth Hospital. The
fifth person, a 61-year-old man, is still under observation in Tuen Mun
Hospital. The sixth person, a 48-year-old woman, was discharged yesterday.
It is suspected that the couple contracted the disease from a passenger, a
man aged 73, who sat close to them on their way to Beijing. The man was
feeling unwell after visiting his brother in Ward 8A of Prince of Wales
Hospital earlier this month.
DH has informed the Airport Authority, the Civil Aviation Department and
the airline concerned. Advice was also given to the airline concerned to
disinfect the airplanes.
DH is tracing the crew members and passengers who had taken these two
flights, for surveillance purposes.
The spokesman reminded members of the public who have respiratory symptoms
including fever, chills, malaise and cough to avoid traveling by plane
before recovery.
It is prudent for tourists to adopt the following precautionary measures to
prevent atypical pneumonia:
Build up good body immunity by having a proper diet, regular exercise and
adequate rest, reducing stress and avoiding smoking;
Maintain good personal hygiene, and wash hands after sneezing, coughing or
cleaning the nose;
Maintain good ventilation; avoid visiting crowded places with poor ventilation;
Do not share towels;
Consult a doctor promptly if you develop respiratory symptoms and fever.
--
